Business Context:¶

We are a Team of Human Resources (HR) Professionals, specialise in Diversity and Equality. Our current assignment is to assess a company's equality of Gender.¶

Part 2. The primary focus for this section of analysis is to assess the Equality of the comapny.¶

The Hypothesis is: There is a strong relationship between Monthly Income and Gender.:¶

(That is a certain group of employees (Male or Female enjoys higher Monthly Income)¶¶

H0 = Monthly Income is related to Gender.¶

H1 = Monthly Income is NOT related to Gender.¶

H0 = Monthly Income is dependent on Gender H1 = Monthly Income is not dependent on Gender

$\begin{align} & {{H}_{0}}:\,\mu =\,{{\mu }_{0}} \\ & {{H}_{1}}:\,\mu \ne {{\mu }_{0}} \\ \end{align}$

2. Anderson-Darling Test¶

In [71]:
result = anderson(mi_data)

print('stat=%.2f' % (result.statistic))
for i in range(len(result.critical_values)):
    significance_level, critical_Value = result.significance_level[i], result.critical_values[i]
    if result.statistic < critical_Value:
        print('Approximately Normally Distributed at %.2f%% level' % (significance_level))
    else:
        print('Not Approximately Normally Distributed %.2f%% level' % (significance_level))

stat=8.08
Not Approximately Normally Distributed 15.00% level
Not Approximately Normally Distributed 10.00% level
Not Approximately Normally Distributed 5.00% level
Not Approximately Normally Distributed 2.50% level
Not Approximately Normally Distributed 1.00% level

Step 10: Anova Test¶

In [77]:
#using anova test to confirm hypothesis

model = smf.ols('MonthlyIncome ~ C(Gender)', data=df1).fit()  
aov_table = anova_lm(model, typ=2)

print(aov_table)

                 sum_sq      df         F    PR(>F)
C(Gender)  1.106419e+06     1.0  0.176648  0.674342
Residual   7.898178e+09  1261.0       NaN       NaN
In [78]:
mcTreatment    = multi.MultiComparison(df1['MonthlyIncome'], df1['Gender'])
results_Treatment  = mcTreatment.tukeyhsd()  
#tukey will do multiple comparison

print(results_Treatment.summary())

  Multiple Comparison of Means - Tukey HSD, FWER=0.05  
=======================================================
group1 group2 meandiff p-adj    lower    upper   reject
-------------------------------------------------------
Female   Male -60.6726 0.6853 -343.8796 222.5343  False
-------------------------------------------------------

Observation 8:¶

The family-wise error rate is 0.05 (aka FWER) as default¶

p-value : 0.6853 Test is run in group 1 vs group 2:

  • permutation: Female vs Male shows reject as False
  • this means they are not significantly different as we fail to reject null hypo
  • the confidence interval is -343.8796 to 222.5343, which includes 0 value, which implies its not significantly different

Conclusion:¶

Basing on Anova Test results, we reject H0 and concluded that there is no difference between Female and Male in Monthly Income.¶

Accepting Alternative Hypothesis (Monthly Income is NOT dependent of Gender): $\begin{align}¶

& {{H}{1}}:\,\mu \ne {{\mu }{0}} \ \end{align}$

Business Conclusion:¶

1. There is an equal distribution of the monthly income between the rows 0-500 and 501-1000 even though the distribution AFTER transformation suggests that the distribution is not normal.¶

2. Based on the variance test and the visual box plots, we can conclude that there is no income inequality amongst Males and Females.¶
